===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|wir|lang=enm}}, {{term|wyr|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|wir|wīr|wire, metal thread, wire-ornament|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|wīraz||wire|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|weyro-||a twist, thread, cord, wire|lang=ine-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|wey-||to turn, twist, weave, plait|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|Wir||wire|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Wiere||wire, metallic thread|lang=de}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|vír||wire|lang=is}}, Swedish {{term|vira||to twist|lang=sv}}, Latin {{term|vieo|vieō|weave together|lang=la}}, Welsh [[gwyr]] ('bent'), and Greek [[ίρις]] ('rainbow').

